621
00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:16.543
- Our history is shaped
by migration and conflict.

622
00:34:18.585 --> 00:34:22.210
In the 19th century.
European immigrants moved west

623
00:34:22.293 --> 00:34:24.377
into the homelands
of the Dakota Sioux

624
00:34:24.460 --> 00:34:27.543
in the central U.S.
and Canada.

625
00:34:27.627 --> 00:34:29.752
After a series
of broken treaties.

626
00:34:29.835 --> 00:34:31.752
wars. and public hangings.

627
00:34:31.835 --> 00:34:34.710
the Dakota were driven out
by the U.S. government

628
00:34:34.794 --> 00:34:37.752
and scattered
to small reservations.

629
00:34:37.835 --> 00:34:39.877
The Flandreau Santee Sioux

630
00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:42.752
settled on land
near Sioux Falls.

631
00:34:46.794 --> 00:34:48.752
- Where we're located here
in Flandreau.

632
00:34:48.835 --> 00:34:50.377
we were two to three hours

633
00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:53.251
from all other
Dakota communities.

634
00:34:53.335 --> 00:34:55.418
so we all stay in touch.

635
00:34:55.502 --> 00:34:57.293
- Anywhere we go.
we're Dakota.

636
00:34:57.377 --> 00:35:00.085
Don't matter if we're in DC
or we're in China

637
00:35:00.168 --> 00:35:01.585
or we're here in the homelands.

638
00:35:01.669 --> 00:35:04.126
We'll be Dakota.

639
00:35:04.210 --> 00:35:06.251
- How many here?
300 and some here on rez?

640
00:35:06.335 --> 00:35:08.251
- Yeah.
Close to it. yeah.

641
00:35:08.335 --> 00:35:12.460
- And total. 500. 600?
- About 600. 700.

642
00:35:12.543 --> 00:35:14.585
- There was a thing called
Indian Court of Offenses

643
00:35:14.669 --> 00:35:16.251
back in the day.

644
00:35:16.335 --> 00:35:19.251
We weren't even allowed
to gather like this.

645
00:35:19.335 --> 00:35:20.919
"Kill the Indian.
save the man."

646
00:35:21.001 --> 00:35:22.960
The boarding-school era.

647
00:35:23.043 --> 00:35:25.960
Started cutting our hair.
putting us in little suits.

648
00:35:26.043 --> 00:35:27.960
putting us in boarding schools.

649
00:35:28.043 --> 00:35:31.919
To speak to culture.
the language.

650
00:35:32.001 --> 00:35:33.835
you were punished.

651
00:35:33.919 --> 00:35:36.669
And then the freedom
of religion was. like. in 1978.

652
00:35:36.752 --> 00:35:38.001
That's not that long ago.

653
00:35:38.085 --> 00:35:40.627
So his grandpa. my dad.

654
00:35:40.710 --> 00:35:43.794
they were both fluent speakers.
but...

655
00:35:43.877 --> 00:35:46.168
sometimes it was hard
for them to speak

656
00:35:46.251 --> 00:35:47.877
just because of that era.

657
00:35:47.960 --> 00:35:49.752
- My older relatives.
grandparents and whatnot.

658
00:35:49.835 --> 00:35:53.502
they were forced off the
reservation to find employment.

659
00:35:53.585 --> 00:35:55.835
to make better lives.
if you will.

660
00:35:55.919 --> 00:35:57.835
in the eyes of
the United States government.

661
00:35:57.919 --> 00:36:00.960
- Growing up in Minneapolis.

662
00:36:01.043 --> 00:36:04.085
we just knew we were Indian.

663
00:36:04.168 --> 00:36:06.835
We knew that we went
to the little Indian programs.

664
00:36:06.919 --> 00:36:09.669
and that was about it.

665
00:36:09.752 --> 00:36:14.001
I had no idea of the history
that I was born in

666
00:36:14.085 --> 00:36:15.126
from the land.

667
00:36:19.585 --> 00:36:21.960
- The Royal River Casino
opened in 1990.

668
00:36:22.043 --> 00:36:24.001
The tribe runs it.

669
00:36:24.085 --> 00:36:25.877
At that time.
we were the only show in town.

670
00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:27.126
- Awesome.
- All right.

671
00:36:29.251 --> 00:36:32.126
- The casino itself
is a huge economic engine.

672
00:36:32.210 --> 00:36:34.669
not only for Flandreau.
but the surrounding areas.

673
00:36:34.752 --> 00:36:38.335
The impact.
it multiplies everywhere else.

674
00:36:38.418 --> 00:36:40.001
- Brought a lot
of the economy back.

675
00:36:40.085 --> 00:36:42.293
and it brought a lot
of people back. too.

676
00:36:42.377 --> 00:36:43.835
- Come on. come on.

677
00:36:43.919 --> 00:36:46.168
- And it provides
for social programs.

678
00:36:46.251 --> 00:36:47.669
everything
that the tribe needs--

679
00:36:47.752 --> 00:36:49.001
government services.

680
00:36:49.085 --> 00:36:51.001
You can say it helped
springboard us

681
00:36:51.085 --> 00:36:53.210
into the revitalization
of the language program.

682
00:36:53.293 --> 00:36:56.126
- How many people speak Dakota?

683
00:36:56.210 --> 00:37:00.377
- Well. I can speak
for just this community.

684
00:37:00.460 --> 00:37:02.043
Maybe three.

685
00:37:02.126 --> 00:37:04.585
The tribe here made the effort

686
00:37:04.669 --> 00:37:08.085
to push for
a language-immersion class.

687
00:37:09.919 --> 00:37:12.543
Who are we
if we don't have our language?

688
00:37:44.335 --> 00:37:46.919
- Powwows--it's not just
for one tribe.

689
00:37:47.001 --> 00:37:48.710
It's many tribes.

690
00:37:48.794 --> 00:37:50.460
We may not all speak
the same language.

691
00:37:50.543 --> 00:37:52.251
but we all come together.

692
00:37:55.043 --> 00:37:59.085
I'm Santee Dakota.
Ho-Chunk and Meskwaki.

693
00:37:59.168 --> 00:38:00.418
As Native Americans.

694
00:38:00.502 --> 00:38:03.794
I think it's real important
to have that cultural identity

695
00:38:03.877 --> 00:38:07.418
for dancing and beadwork
and crafts and leatherwork.

696
00:38:07.502 --> 00:38:09.752
I tell my kids. I said.
"You guys have to learn this.

697
00:38:09.835 --> 00:38:12.794
because when I'm gone.
there's not gonna be anybody."

698
00:38:19.168 --> 00:38:21.585
A lot of Natives have never
been exposed to culture.

699
00:38:21.669 --> 00:38:23.001
you know. like this.

700
00:38:23.085 --> 00:38:24.919
And if we can get more people

701
00:38:25.001 --> 00:38:26.585
to be courageous
and get out there

702
00:38:26.669 --> 00:38:28.585
in the center
and dance with us...

703
00:38:28.669 --> 00:38:30.251
Just listen to the music.

704
00:38:30.335 --> 00:38:32.335
and you'll get the rhythm
and you'll go.

705
00:38:38.752 --> 00:38:41.960
- Last night at the Wacipi.
there's a little girl.

706
00:38:42.043 --> 00:38:43.794
and she looked at me.
and she said...

707
00:38:45.377 --> 00:38:46.585
That was saying hello.

708
00:38:46.669 --> 00:38:48.251
And then all the other little
girls around them

709
00:38:48.335 --> 00:38:50.627
were saying... .
"Hello. hello."

710
00:38:50.710 --> 00:38:55.460
It gets emotional to just hear
them speak their language.

711
00:38:57.502 --> 00:39:00.543
- It's saving our life.
It's saving our kids.

712
00:39:00.627 --> 00:39:03.710
It's giving a chance.
a future...

713
00:39:03.794 --> 00:39:06.669
for us to continue.

714
00:39:27.126 --> 00:39:29.877
- The dark chapters
in American history

715
00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:32.335
are still unfolding
in life today.

716
00:39:35.752 --> 00:39:39.001
In our travels. we've been
struck by how differently

717
00:39:39.085 --> 00:39:41.418
different communities
approach their past...

718
00:39:43.960 --> 00:39:47.752
And which parts of it they
embrace and which they avoid.

719
00:39:49.794 --> 00:39:53.377
Columbus. Mississippi. is
on the geological Black Belt.

720
00:39:53.460 --> 00:39:56.919
a band of fertile soil
dating back millions of years.

721
00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:01.585
The soil made it a good place
for plantations.

722
00:40:06.460 --> 00:40:10.835
In Columbus. antebellum
mansions are reminders

723
00:40:10.919 --> 00:40:12.919
of life
during the Confederacy.

724
00:40:17.126 --> 00:40:21.085
The markers in
Friendship Cemetery are. too.

725
00:40:26.835 --> 00:40:28.418
After slavery ended.

726
00:40:28.502 --> 00:40:30.752
Jim Crow laws
and civil rights abuses

727
00:40:30.835 --> 00:40:33.377
into the 20th century
and beyond

728
00:40:33.460 --> 00:40:36.919
are things to be reckoned with
across the country.

729
00:40:46.001 --> 00:40:49.877
Sandfield is Columbus'
historic Black cemetery.

730
00:40:49.960 --> 00:40:54.085
- Today we are so elated
to stand here and tell you

731
00:40:54.168 --> 00:40:57.752
that we have a marker
for Sandfield Cemetery.

732
00:40:57.835 --> 00:41:01.126
Established before
the Civil War.

733
00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.794
among people buried here
are Robert Gleed.

734
00:41:03.877 --> 00:41:07.460
a former slave who served
in the state senate.

735
00:41:07.543 --> 00:41:12.168
Reflect back. lest we forget
our history and our heritage.

736
00:41:12.251 --> 00:41:16.418
all:

737
00:41:27.085 --> 00:41:30.502
- We're here today because
on the 8th of May in 1865.

738
00:41:30.585 --> 00:41:32.293
Union troops arrived
in Columbus.

739
00:41:32.377 --> 00:41:35.502
That is effectively
when enslavement ended.

740
00:41:35.585 --> 00:41:37.293
- Chuck Yarborough teaches

741
00:41:37.377 --> 00:41:40.502
at the Mississippi School
for Mathematics & Science.

742
00:41:40.585 --> 00:41:42.627
It's a public high school.
and every year

743
00:41:42.710 --> 00:41:46.543
