00:41:57.585 --> 00:41:58.502
- Yeah.
- Like...

751
00:41:58.585 --> 00:42:00.210
- There's some specificity
to that

752
00:42:00.293 --> 00:42:03.168
that's even more
ominous feeling. right? Okay.

753
00:42:03.251 --> 00:42:04.669
- So the first thing
that you'll notice that--

754
00:42:04.752 --> 00:42:05.919
- In the archives.

755
00:42:06.001 --> 00:42:09.669
students learn about life
in Columbus 150 years ago.

756
00:42:09.752 --> 00:42:11.377
- But even right here.

757
00:42:11.460 --> 00:42:15.168
you can find
"one Negro woman named Milly."

758
00:42:15.251 --> 00:42:16.669
- Finding the Milly
that was associated

759
00:42:16.752 --> 00:42:19.001
with this court case
is a whole nother thing.

760
00:42:19.085 --> 00:42:21.960
- Then they write scripts
to perform in the cemetery

761
00:42:22.043 --> 00:42:23.627
on Emancipation Day.

762
00:42:23.710 --> 00:42:27.669
- Good afternoon.
good people of Columbus.

763
00:42:27.752 --> 00:42:29.543
although my experience ought
to have taught me

764
00:42:29.627 --> 00:42:32.877
that the people of Columbus
aren't always so good.

765
00:42:32.960 --> 00:42:35.377
- The next document
we're going to look at--

766
00:42:35.460 --> 00:42:39.377
page one and two
of the newspapers.

767
00:42:39.460 --> 00:42:41.085
It says.
"Columbus. Mississippi.

768
00:42:41.168 --> 00:42:43.543
November 3. 1875."

769
00:42:43.627 --> 00:42:45.168
- "Under these instructions.

770
00:42:45.251 --> 00:42:47.418
"a number of Negroes
were arrested

771
00:42:47.502 --> 00:42:50.251
"and turned over
to the proper police officers.

772
00:42:50.335 --> 00:42:53.085
"I regret to state
that the following Negroes

773
00:42:53.168 --> 00:42:54.543
were shot and killed."

774
00:42:54.627 --> 00:42:56.919
- And as we move
through downtown.

775
00:42:57.001 --> 00:43:00.043
a mob led
by Jacob Hunter Sharp

776
00:43:00.126 --> 00:43:01.710
attacked us.

777
00:43:01.794 --> 00:43:03.543
They shot into our group.

778
00:43:03.627 --> 00:43:07.502
killing four innocent Black men
and wounding three others.

779
00:43:07.585 --> 00:43:09.710
- Makes them way more brave
in my eyes

780
00:43:09.794 --> 00:43:12.418
because. like.
they're actively. like.

781
00:43:12.502 --> 00:43:13.418
threatening to kill them

782
00:43:13.502 --> 00:43:15.210
and telling them
how they're gonna do it.

783
00:43:15.293 --> 00:43:17.752
- The ex-Confederates didn't
stop with the rumor. though.

784
00:43:17.835 --> 00:43:19.877
We received a letter
threatening death

785
00:43:19.960 --> 00:43:22.418
if we continued to educate
the freed people.

786
00:43:22.502 --> 00:43:23.543
- I think this actually shows

787
00:43:23.627 --> 00:43:25.043
that the people
who threatened them

788
00:43:25.126 --> 00:43:28.251
understood the importance
of education

789
00:43:28.335 --> 00:43:29.710
and how it could
be problematic

790
00:43:29.794 --> 00:43:31.585
if people knew
how to read and how to write.

791
00:43:31.669 --> 00:43:33.293
Taking away the education

792
00:43:33.377 --> 00:43:35.418
keeps the community
in a submissive position.

793
00:43:35.502 --> 00:43:37.585
and they would do that
by any means necessary.

794
00:43:37.669 --> 00:43:39.585
- I feel like my story

795
00:43:39.669 --> 00:43:41.794
is just the ultimate
American success story.

796
00:43:41.877 --> 00:43:45.752
I am the son of a man
and a woman who were enslaved.

797
00:43:45.835 --> 00:43:48.877
But my father bought his
freedom before the Civil War.

798
00:43:48.960 --> 00:43:51.126
- Some of you
mistakenly believe

799
00:43:51.210 --> 00:43:54.168
that only men helped establish
this community.

800
00:43:54.251 --> 00:43:57.627
but let me let y'all in
on a little secret.

801
00:43:57.710 --> 00:43:59.919
Behind every strong man.

802
00:44:00.001 --> 00:44:02.919
there is an equally
if not stronger woman.

803
00:44:05.377 --> 00:44:08.126
- I'm Mississippi State Senator
Robert Gleed.

804
00:44:08.210 --> 00:44:09.835
a notable business owner
and political leader

805
00:44:09.919 --> 00:44:11.794
in Columbus and Lowndes County.

806
00:44:11.877 --> 00:44:13.627
Now. I used to tell
my children.

807
00:44:13.710 --> 00:44:16.960
"We all stand on the shoulders
of someone who came before us."

808
00:44:17.043 --> 00:44:18.794
We had our setbacks
as a country

809
00:44:18.877 --> 00:44:20.335
and as a people in our day.

810
00:44:20.418 --> 00:44:23.752
but it's clear
that progress has been made.

811
00:44:23.835 --> 00:44:26.460
And I like to think
that you folks can reach higher

812
00:44:26.543 --> 00:44:28.293
even when times are tough.

813
00:44:28.377 --> 00:44:29.669
'cause those many years ago.

814
00:44:29.752 --> 00:44:33.085
I offered my shoulders
for you to stand on.

815
00:44:33.168 --> 00:44:36.210
and I hope you'll do the same
for those that follow you.

816
00:44:49.210 --> 00:44:51.168
- When I moved here
from New York.

817
00:44:51.251 --> 00:44:54.043
I experienced a little racism.

818
00:44:54.126 --> 00:44:57.001
You know.
I was managing this hotel.

819
00:44:57.085 --> 00:44:59.502
and some guests
did not understand

820
00:44:59.585 --> 00:45:03.251
that I was the manager.
that it wasn't anyone above me.

821
00:45:03.335 --> 00:45:04.960
But as the town began to grow

822
00:45:05.043 --> 00:45:07.293
and I began to meet
more people.

823
00:45:07.377 --> 00:45:11.669
there's more of an acceptance
of African American people

824
00:45:11.752 --> 00:45:13.210
getting
in leadership position.

825
00:45:13.293 --> 00:45:14.710
management position.

826
00:45:14.794 --> 00:45:19.543
It takes some getting used to.
and it's not all of the South.

827
00:45:19.627 --> 00:45:24.043
The younger generation is
very accepting of diversity.

828
00:45:24.126 --> 00:45:26.877
They are making that change.

829
00:45:26.960 --> 00:45:28.210
The past is the past.

830
00:45:28.293 --> 00:45:31.543
and Mississippi is striving
for change.

831
00:45:48.752 --> 00:45:50.877
- Factories around Columbus
used to make things

832
00:45:50.960 --> 00:45:55.335
like blue jeans. hot dogs.
pork chops. and toilet seats.

833
00:45:55.418 --> 00:46:00.126
Those industries disappeared.
leaving 20% unemployment

834
00:46:00.210 --> 00:46:03.085
in the poorest state
in the country.

835
00:46:03.168 --> 00:46:05.418
Getting out of that kind
of depression

836
00:46:05.502 --> 00:46:06.877
doesn't just happen.

837
00:46:06.960 --> 00:46:08.502
It takes community action.

838
00:46:10.669 --> 00:46:11.794
The region around Columbus

839
00:46:11.877 --> 00:46:14.585
started a development agency
called LINK

840
00:46:14.669 --> 00:46:17.752
that's brought in lots
of high-tech manufacturers.

841
00:46:17.835 --> 00:46:20.794
- If it can be done here.
it can be done anywhere.

842
00:46:20.877 --> 00:46:22.877
- Convincing companies
to move here

843
00:46:22.960 --> 00:46:26.043
is the job of Joe Max Higgins
and Brenda Latham.

844
00:46:26.126 --> 00:46:28.043
- And we've built
a new industrial park

845
00:46:28.126 --> 00:46:29.585
and are in the process

846
00:46:29.669 --> 00:46:32.210
of doing a new industrial park
in Starkville.

847
00:46:32.293 --> 00:46:35.085
- We found a niche
in advanced manufacturing.

848
00:46:35.168 --> 00:46:37.585
We acquire property.
We install infrastructure.

849
00:46:37.669 --> 00:46:38.752
We locate companies.

850
00:46:38.835 --> 00:46:40.460
And if it all works out well.

851
00:46:40.543 --> 00:46:43.001
we get that company in. and
we get 'em going and running.

852
00:46:43.085 --> 00:46:45.126
Then we go and we do
another one and another one.

853
00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:46.835
But first thing we got to do
a lot of times

854
00:46:46.919 --> 00:46:50.835
is just put aside issues
or concerns or beliefs

855
00:46:50.919 --> 00:46:52.627
that may not be true.

856
00:46:52.710 --> 00:46:54.627
You know. people tell us
we're last in everything good.

857
00:46:55.710 --> 00:46:57.293
- Well. I mean.
that's the rap we have.

858
00:46:57.377 --> 00:47:00.460
whether it's true or not--
we're last in everything good.

859
00:47:00.543 --> 00:47:03.251
- Mississippi was
the last state to still have

860
00:47:03.335 --> 00:47:06.669
the Confederate stars and bars
on its state flag.

861
00:47:09.543 --> 00:47:12.502
- Columbus has a foot
in antebellum

862
00:47:12.585 --> 00:47:13.960
and a foot in the future.

863
00:47:14.043 --> 00:47:16.543
Some days
they almost feel confused.

864
00:47:16.627 --> 00:47:18.293
And when I got here. I said.

865
00:47:18.377 --> 00:47:20.502
"Before I take this job.
answer a question for me.

866
00:47:20.585 --> 00:47:21.835
"Are you a community

867
00:47:21.919 --> 00:47:24.460
that values your past
more than your future?"

868
00:47:24.543 --> 00:47:26.460
They said. "Oh. no."

869
00:47:26.543 --> 00:47:28.293
Now. look.
I understand heritage.

870
00:47:28.377 --> 00:47:29.669
and I understand culture.

871
00:47:29.752 --> 00:47:32.710
but if you may offend somebody
that might want to invest here

872
00:47:32.794 --> 00:47:36.210
and create jobs here.
why would you do that?

873
00:47:47.752 --> 00:47:50.877
- It's a real shock when
traditional jobs disappear...

874
00:47:50.960 --> 00:47:54.126
- The future will be working
alongside the robots.

875
00:47:54.210 --> 00:47:56.001
- And the new ones call
for skills

876
00:47:56.085 --> 00:47:58.126
that local people don't have.

877
00:47:58.210 --> 00:48:00.335
As we've seen
around the country.

878
00:48:00.418 --> 00:48:02.710
community colleges
are incredibly important

879
00:48:02.794 --> 00:48:05.502
in preparing students
for new jobs

880
00:48:05.585 --> 00:48:09.877
and. in the bigger picture.
fighting inequality.

881
00:48:09.960 --> 00:48:13.960
This is the Communiversity
near Columbus. Mississippi.

882
00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:18.377
- This is highly technical.

883
00:48:18.460 --> 00:48:20.377
It is not the old shop.

884
00:48:20.460 --> 00:48:23.377
The old vocational school
was sometimes

885
00:48:23.460 --> 00:48:26.210
a penalty a person paid.

886
00:48:26.293 --> 00:48:28.377
- Press at every station.

887
00:48:28.460 --> 00:48:30.043
- We are second chances

888
00:48:30.126 --> 00:48:33.502
for people to get
that high-school equivalency.

889
00:48:33.585 --> 00:48:35.543
to get a job.

890
00:48:35.627 --> 00:48:37.919
Many individuals
in our community

891
00:48:38.001 --> 00:48:42.418
are one flat tire away
from losing their job

892
00:48:42.502 --> 00:48:45.126
or not finishing
their education.

893
00:48:45.210 --> 00:48:49.460
We help bring partners
to removing those barriers.

894
00:48:49.543 --> 00:48:53.752
We lift up the community
as a whole.

895
00:48:53.835 --> 00:48:57.960
- That's the best description
of community college

896
00:48:58.043 --> 00:49:01.126
and what you do
that I've heard anywhere.

897
00:49:01.210 --> 00:49:03.877
- If it can happen here

898
00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:06.710
in the poorest of all states.

899
00:49:06.794 --> 00:49:09.919
then surely the positive things

900
00:49:10.001 --> 00:49:12.251
are replicable elsewhere.

901
00:49:20.502 --> 00:49:21.627
- You go into this business

902
00:49:21.710 --> 00:49:23.251
because you love
this business.

903
00:49:23.335 --> 00:49:25.126
because it is
the most interesting way

904
00:49:25.210 --> 00:49:28.126
you can possibly spend
your life.

905
00:49:28.210 --> 00:49:31.585
An unexpected truth about
most people who are reporters.

906
00:49:31.669 --> 00:49:32.794
including me.

907
00:49:32.877 --> 00:49:35.919
almost all
professional reporters

908
00:49:36.001 --> 00:49:39.210
are psychologically introverts
and shy.

909
00:49:39.293 --> 00:49:43.794
And so you are looking
for a structural excuse

910
00:49:43.877 --> 00:49:45.960
to go out in the world.
meet people.

911
00:49:46.043 --> 00:49:47.251
and ask them about things.

912
00:49:47.335 --> 00:49:50.126
If I'm just on the street.
I'm not gonna talk to anybody.

913
00:49:50.210 --> 00:49:52.293
But if I'm on the street
as a reporter.

914
00:49:52.377 --> 00:49:54.126
I'm gonna talk to everybody.

915
00:49:54.210 --> 00:49:57.126
I have a license to say.
"Tell me your story.

916
00:49:57.210 --> 00:49:59.794
Tell me your hopes.
Tell me what I don't know."

917
00:49:59.877 --> 00:50:03.502
There's this secret power
that being a journalist gives

918
00:50:03.585 --> 00:50:06.502
to almost everybody I know
in this business.

919
00:50:14.919 --> 00:50:17.627
- At the far eastern tip
of the United States

920
00:50:17.710 --> 00:50:21.168
is the tiny town
of Eastport. Maine.

921
00:50:21.251 --> 00:50:24.335
- When we very first came here
in 2013. I did an article.

922
00:50:24.418 --> 00:50:28.335
Its headline was.
"The Little Town That Might."

923
00:50:28.418 --> 00:50:30.877
The conclusion was.
"Will Eastport make it?

924
00:50:30.960 --> 00:50:32.669
I don't know."

925
00:50:32.752 --> 00:50:36.502
Eastport has the deepest port
on the East Coast.

926
00:50:36.585 --> 00:50:39.168
On the other hand.
it's so far away.

927
00:50:42.251 --> 00:50:44.502
- There are just
not many people--

928
00:50:44.585 --> 00:50:46.210
1.300 people

929
00:50:46.293 --> 00:50:48.210
in a town that used to have
about 10.000

930
00:50:48.293 --> 00:50:51.210
in its heyday
of sardine fishing.

931
00:50:51.293 --> 00:50:54.585
The town has had
so many surprising disasters

932
00:50:54.669 --> 00:50:56.043
come their way.

933
00:50:56.126 --> 00:50:59.043
Everything on Main Street
burned down in 1887

934
00:50:59.126 --> 00:51:01.085
or just before.
and they had to rebuild

935
00:51:01.168 --> 00:51:03.251
the entire main street
of the town.

936
00:51:03.335 --> 00:51:06.168
which they have
in a beautiful fashion.

937
00:51:13.460 --> 00:51:14.794
- That was a sardine place.

938
00:51:14.877 --> 00:51:16.877
That was the last one in this
area. wasn't it. Dickie?

939
00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:18.919
- It was '83
I started working there.

940
00:51:19.001 --> 00:51:20.710
And I got laid off
'cause there was no fish.

941
00:51:20.794 --> 00:51:22.043
so I went blueberry raking.

942
00:51:22.126 --> 00:51:23.919
Happiest phone call I ever got.
Said. "We got fish."

943
00:51:24.001 --> 00:51:27.251
I said. "I'll be back."

944
00:51:27.335 --> 00:51:30.085
Man. that clam digging.
Nope.

945
00:51:31.335 --> 00:51:32.752
- You have to love
living here.

946
00:51:32.835 --> 00:51:33.919
If you don't love living here.

947
00:51:34.001 --> 00:51:36.585
you wouldn't put the work in
that it requires.

948
00:51:36.669 --> 00:51:39.460
People are doing one. two.
three different things.

949
00:51:39.543 --> 00:51:41.919
I'm the executive director
of the Port Authority.

950
00:51:42.001 --> 00:51:44.627
I'm also a reserve police
officer here in town.

951
00:51:44.710 --> 00:51:46.710
I'm the chairman
of the county commissioners.

952
00:51:46.794 --> 00:51:49.085
I coach soccer
at a local high school.

953
00:51:49.168 --> 00:51:50.919
And--oh. and my wife and I.

954
00:51:51.001 --> 00:51:53.794
we flip real estate on the side
in our spare time.

955
00:51:53.877 --> 00:51:57.585
That's the commitment that
you have to put in to be here.

956
00:51:57.669 --> 00:51:59.794
It is a different type
of person.

957
00:51:59.877 --> 00:52:01.085
"Resourceful" is probably

958
00:52:01.168 --> 00:52:02.919
the best word
that I can come up with.

959
00:52:08.794 --> 00:52:10.460
- I'd say there's
kind of two Eastports.

960
00:52:10.543 --> 00:52:12.001
Right now we're
in the colored Eastport.

961
00:52:12.085 --> 00:52:13.794
It's summertime. and there's
a lot of people around.

962
00:52:13.877 --> 00:52:16.627
There's things
constantly happening.

963
00:52:16.710 --> 00:52:20.335
And then there's sepia-toned
Eastport in the wintertime.

964
00:52:20.418 --> 00:52:22.710
where everything
kind of calms down.

965
00:52:22.794 --> 00:52:24.126
A lot of the colors go away.

966
00:52:24.210 --> 00:52:29.168
but it's also a cleanse
spiritually and for your mind.

967
00:52:34.543 --> 00:52:36.960
I'm 17. I'm a senior
at Shead High School.

968
00:52:37.043 --> 00:52:39.460
and I also take
online college classes

969
00:52:39.543 --> 00:52:41.835
with the UMaine system.

970
00:52:41.919 --> 00:52:44.335
And I'll going on to either go
to Maine Maritime

971
00:52:44.418 --> 00:52:46.335
for marine transportations
and operations.

972
00:52:46.418 --> 00:52:48.669
or I'll be headed off
to a trade school.

973
00:52:53.251 --> 00:52:55.001
I moved to Eastport
seven. eight years ago

974
00:52:55.085 --> 00:52:56.710
with my parents
from the Jersey Shore.

975
00:52:56.794 --> 00:52:59.210
I've kind of seen
how city life is.

976
00:52:59.293 --> 00:53:01.293
I much prefer this.

977
00:53:01.377 --> 00:53:04.168
It's summertime right now.
Primarily. I'm a lobsterman.

978
00:53:04.251 --> 00:53:06.669
Spend most of my day in this
fishing aspect of Eastport.

979
00:53:06.752 --> 00:53:08.001
which is one life.

980
00:53:08.085 --> 00:53:09.835
but then I'll go home.
and I'll shower.

981
00:53:09.919 --> 00:53:12.168
and I go out to the arts center
to a gallery opening

982
00:53:12.251 --> 00:53:14.418
or a gig
or a classical concert.

983
00:53:21.669 --> 00:53:22.835
With climate change and all.

984
00:53:22.919 --> 00:53:24.210
I'm not really expecting
to fish

985
00:53:24.293 --> 00:53:26.001
for more than 15 years
lobstering.

986
00:53:26.085 --> 00:53:28.210
I think it's gonna move north.

987
00:53:28.293 --> 00:53:30.001
I think we're gonna have
more opportunities

988
00:53:30.085 --> 00:53:31.460
for the oysters and mussels.

989
00:53:31.543 --> 00:53:33.168
and I'd like to take my
lobstering money and put that

990
00:53:33.251 --> 00:53:35.043
into a sustainable
aquaculture business.

991
00:53:35.126 --> 00:53:36.710
employing a lot
of local people.

992
00:53:36.794 --> 00:53:39.335
but I think lobstering's gonna
go away.

993
00:54:09.168 --> 00:54:12.502
- In 2003. a group called
The Women of the Commons

994
00:54:12.585 --> 00:54:15.293
renovated a run-down building
down the waterfront.

995
00:54:15.377 --> 00:54:19.126
making a shop and gallery
space for local artists.

996
00:54:19.210 --> 00:54:21.752
- 2003. there were a lot
of boarded-up buildings.

997
00:54:21.835 --> 00:54:25.251
They were a new kind of energy
for the downtown.

998
00:54:25.335 --> 00:54:27.460
Okay. just checking.
