00:55:27.502 --> 00:55:29.251
- My interaction with the tide

1021
00:55:29.335 --> 00:55:31.627
has been to wrap the pilings

1022
00:55:31.710 --> 00:55:34.794
of this old sardine factory.

1023
00:55:34.877 --> 00:55:35.960
I came up from Brooklyn.

1024
00:55:36.043 --> 00:55:38.627
and we get a month
in this little town

1025
00:55:38.710 --> 00:55:40.460
and make work based on it.

1026
00:55:42.085 --> 00:55:44.168
Eastport. it's amazing.

1027
00:55:44.251 --> 00:55:47.669
People are cool and weird.

1028
00:55:47.752 --> 00:55:48.960
and I'm weird.

1029
00:56:01.627 --> 00:56:04.168
- The Passamaquoddy tribes
near Eastport

1030
00:56:04.251 --> 00:56:06.669
celebrate their history
every summer.

1031
00:56:06.752 --> 00:56:09.877
- We're proud Passamaquoddies
of this time of year

1032
00:56:09.960 --> 00:56:11.293
and all the time.

1033
00:56:13.251 --> 00:56:15.669
- The Ancestral Paddle really
symbolizes what we've done

1034
00:56:15.752 --> 00:56:16.919
for thousands of years

1035
00:56:17.001 --> 00:56:19.710
using the waterways
to sustain ourselves.

1036
00:56:26.794 --> 00:56:30.835
- In its time.
Eastport has found and lost

1037
00:56:30.919 --> 00:56:33.669
so many ways
of sustaining itself.

1038
00:56:35.418 --> 00:56:38.210
It was once one of the busiest
shipping ports

1039
00:56:38.293 --> 00:56:40.669
till shipping went elsewhere.

1040
00:56:40.752 --> 00:56:43.877
There were
13 sardine canneries

1041
00:56:43.960 --> 00:56:45.794
on the waterfront.

1042
00:56:45.877 --> 00:56:48.502
but that industry moved
to Canada.

1043
00:56:51.960 --> 00:56:53.710
Traditional salmon fishing
ended

1044
00:56:53.794 --> 00:56:56.669
when the wild fish
were depleted.

1045
00:56:56.752 --> 00:56:58.669
Now there are salmon farms.

1046
00:57:05.710 --> 00:57:08.919
The town has invested millions
in the cargo pier

1047
00:57:09.001 --> 00:57:12.585
so they can ship wood pulp
from Maine forests.

1048
00:57:12.669 --> 00:57:14.293
- And we're one
of the last places

1049
00:57:14.377 --> 00:57:17.126
on the East Coast of the U.S..
if not the last place.

1050
00:57:17.210 --> 00:57:19.251
where the forest comes right
to the sea.

1051
00:57:19.335 --> 00:57:23.210
We've done up to 400.000 tons
in one year. just wood pulp.

1052
00:57:26.335 --> 00:57:27.585
- How does a town like this

1053
00:57:27.669 --> 00:57:32.085
keep coming up with new ways
to create a future for itself?

1054
00:57:32.168 --> 00:57:37.085
It's not like Downeast Mainers
are famous for their optimism.

1055
00:57:37.168 --> 00:57:41.085
There's a fine line between
looking for the possibilities

1056
00:57:41.168 --> 00:57:43.085
and denying reality.

1057
00:57:43.168 --> 00:57:45.085
When we lived in China.
we used to joke

1058
00:57:45.168 --> 00:57:47.960
about how all the headlines
in the papers were

1059
00:57:48.043 --> 00:57:51.919
"Happiness Sweeps Nation
as Joy Abounds" or something.

1060
00:57:52.001 --> 00:57:54.168
And so I think that
you don't want to have

1061
00:57:54.251 --> 00:57:57.919
this kind of denying reality
happy talk.

1062
00:57:58.001 --> 00:58:00.126
But sometimes you just have
to try things.

1063
00:58:00.210 --> 00:58:01.669
realistic or not.

1064
00:58:05.877 --> 00:58:08.168
- Pregnant cows.

1065
00:58:08.251 --> 00:58:09.794
In 2010.
we did get a phone call

1066
00:58:09.877 --> 00:58:11.126
from a company
that was interested

1067
00:58:11.210 --> 00:58:13.794
in exporting pregnant
dairy cattle.

1068
00:58:13.877 --> 00:58:15.502
Okay. they want to put
a pregnant cow in a box

1069
00:58:15.585 --> 00:58:18.794
and ship it to parts
all over the world.

1070
00:58:18.877 --> 00:58:20.043
My general manager said.

1071
00:58:20.126 --> 00:58:22.460
"We don't know anything
about shipping pregnant cows."

1072
00:58:22.543 --> 00:58:25.126
I said. "Skip.
neither does anybody else."

1073
00:58:25.210 --> 00:58:28.168
What started off as
a little adventure of 450 cows

1074
00:58:28.251 --> 00:58:30.710
turned into approximately
50.000 head of cattle

1075
00:58:30.794 --> 00:58:34.335
that was exported
through the port of Eastport.

1076
00:58:34.418 --> 00:58:37.877
But the area of Turkey
these cows kind of went to

1077
00:58:37.960 --> 00:58:40.835
was affected mightily
by the Syrian conflict

1078
00:58:40.919 --> 00:58:43.168
there on the border.
and as a result.

1079
00:58:43.251 --> 00:58:46.126
right now that industry
has dried up and stopped.

1080
00:58:46.210 --> 00:58:47.460
You know. geopolitical forces.

1081
00:58:47.543 --> 00:58:50.168
we think. just. you know.
matter on TV.

1082
00:58:50.251 --> 00:58:52.126
But even in a small town.
they can affect

1083
00:58:52.210 --> 00:58:54.919
how many pregnant dairy cattle
we put in a box.

1084
00:59:01.126 --> 00:59:02.794
- Thanks to the Internet.

1085
00:59:02.877 --> 00:59:05.293
small towns have the
same access to national news

1086
00:59:05.377 --> 00:59:07.585
as big cities...

1087
00:59:07.669 --> 00:59:11.001
but local news
is a different story.

1088
00:59:13.126 --> 00:59:14.335
In many towns.

1089
00:59:14.418 --> 00:59:16.877
the local papers
have gone out of business.

1090
00:59:16.960 --> 00:59:18.877
or they're taken over
by investors

1091
00:59:18.960 --> 00:59:20.752
who cut local coverage.

1092
00:59:22.460 --> 00:59:25.794
Eastport's paper
is "The Quoddy Tides."

1093
00:59:25.877 --> 00:59:29.210
- My brother Hugh is director
of the Tides Institute.

1094
00:59:29.293 --> 00:59:30.669
We bookend the downtown.

1095
00:59:30.752 --> 00:59:32.502
with the Tides Institute
on one end

1096
00:59:32.585 --> 00:59:34.502
and "The Quoddy Tides"
on the other end.

1097
00:59:34.585 --> 00:59:37.543
"The Quoddy Tides" started
in 1968 by my mother.

1098
00:59:37.627 --> 00:59:39.502
- Edward French is the editor.

1099
00:59:39.585 --> 00:59:42.043
He publishes it with his wife.
Lora Whelan.

1100
00:59:42.126 --> 00:59:43.377
She's also a reporter.

1101
00:59:43.460 --> 00:59:46.043
- Papers like this
around the country

1102
00:59:46.126 --> 00:59:48.293
are under all kinds
of pressure.

1103
00:59:48.377 --> 00:59:51.752
Your paper is thick. and it is
absolutely full of news

1104
00:59:51.835 --> 00:59:53.543
from 20 correspondents.

1105
00:59:53.627 --> 00:59:54.627
What's your secret?

1106
00:59:54.710 --> 00:59:56.085
- I don't know
that we have a secret.

1107
00:59:56.168 --> 01:00:00.377
but I think it's important for
newspapers not to keep cutting.

1108
01:00:00.460 --> 01:00:02.126
because if you keep cutting.

1109
01:00:02.210 --> 01:00:05.251
there's less and less reason
for people to buy the paper.

1110
01:00:05.335 --> 01:00:06.543
- We try to focus

1111
01:00:06.627 --> 01:00:09.919
in a way that relates directly
to local issues.

1112
01:00:10.001 --> 01:00:11.418
- So we've had
long debates here

1113
01:00:11.502 --> 01:00:14.752
over an oil refinery
or the tribal casinos.

1114
01:00:14.835 --> 01:00:17.085
And we present
what's happened elsewhere.

1115
01:00:17.168 --> 01:00:18.960
Communities that don't have
a local paper.

1116
01:00:19.043 --> 01:00:22.585
the cost for local government
increases. for instance.

1117
01:00:22.669 --> 01:00:26.460
We try not to enter into
the national debate too much.

1118
01:00:26.543 --> 01:00:29.085
It can. particularly
in this polarized time.

1119
01:00:29.168 --> 01:00:30.794
just put people off.

1120
01:00:30.877 --> 01:00:33.502
- Playing the role of the
newspaper in a small community

1121
01:00:33.585 --> 01:00:35.585
is always a delicate balance.

1122
01:00:35.669 --> 01:00:36.960
- I always feel. you know.

1123
01:00:37.043 --> 01:00:40.752
I'm okay as long as there's
no more the half the population

1124
01:00:40.835 --> 01:00:42.126
that crosses over
to the other side

1125
01:00:42.210 --> 01:00:44.168
when I walk down the street
because they don't want

1126
01:00:44.251 --> 01:00:45.502
to talk to me.

1127
01:00:45.585 --> 01:00:47.960
- People will come up to you
or give you a call and say.

1128
01:00:48.043 --> 01:00:49.293
"This is what
I'm worried about.

1129
01:00:49.377 --> 01:00:50.835
"Is there any way
that you can look into it

1130
01:00:50.919 --> 01:00:52.293
and write about it?"

1131
01:00:52.377 --> 01:00:54.627
That's a really
beautiful feeling

1132
01:00:54.710 --> 01:00:56.669
to have someone trust you
like that.

1133
01:00:56.752 --> 01:00:58.085
- Right. right.
- Yeah.

1134
01:00:58.168 --> 01:00:59.502
- We try to provide a voice
for the people

1135
01:00:59.585 --> 01:01:01.502
and the communities
that might otherwise

1136
01:01:01.585 --> 01:01:02.752
might not have a voice

1137
01:01:02.835 --> 01:01:07.627
so that people in power have
to address their concerns.

1138
01:01:07.710 --> 01:01:10.085
I think without
community newspapers.

1139
01:01:10.168 --> 01:01:12.460
democracy will really suffer.

1140
01:01:17.460 --> 01:01:22.168
- We've now been to Eastport
five times in six years.

1141
01:01:22.251 --> 01:01:25.377
Maybe asking
if Eastport will make it

1142
01:01:25.460 --> 01:01:27.669
is the wrong question.

1143
01:01:27.752 --> 01:01:32.418
The town was established
over 200 years ago...

1144
01:01:32.502 --> 01:01:33.794
and Native people were here

1145
01:01:33.877 --> 01:01:36.126
for thousands of years
before that.

1146
01:01:39.126 --> 01:01:43.335
Countless generations
have made a life here...

1147
01:01:43.418 --> 01:01:45.835
and countless more will.

1148
01:02:01.919 --> 01:02:03.627
- When you tell somebody
you're from Eastport. Maine.

1149
01:02:03.710 --> 01:02:05.710
or any small town
for that matter.

1150
01:02:05.794 --> 01:02:07.710
they just assume
that you've never seen

1151
01:02:07.794 --> 01:02:09.210
the bright lights
and the big city.

1152
01:02:09.293 --> 01:02:11.877
They'll look at you and say.
"Well. this is a cell phone.

1153
01:02:11.960 --> 01:02:14.043
You ever seen one
of those before?"

1154
01:02:14.126 --> 01:02:15.043
It's just that belief

1155
01:02:15.126 --> 01:02:16.835
that. somehow.
by living out here.

1156
01:02:16.919 --> 01:02:19.210
we're not as metropolitan
and as savvy

1157
01:02:19.293 --> 01:02:21.627
as to what's going on
with the world.

1158
01:02:21.710 --> 01:02:24.210
I would argue perhaps we know
it even a little better

1159
01:02:24.293 --> 01:02:27.335
because we take the time
to focus on it.

1160
01:02:27.418 --> 01:02:29.377
and that makes us
a whole lot more worldly

1161
01:02:29.460 --> 01:02:30.877
than people believe.

1162
01:02:30.960 --> 01:02:33.293
That's probably one stick jab.
if you will.

1163
01:02:33.377 --> 01:02:34.543
from if you go to a big city

1164
01:02:34.627 --> 01:02:37.085
and somebody finds out you're
from a small town.

1165
01:02:37.168 --> 01:02:40.043
They just assume that you
haven't been paying attention.

1166
01:03:07.168 --> 01:03:10.293
- All of the travel and living
in far-flung places

1167
01:03:10.377 --> 01:03:11.460
that we've done

1168
01:03:11.543 --> 01:03:14.627
has also changed
our relationship in some way.

1169
01:03:14.710 --> 01:03:17.210
I mean.
we're stuck together forever

1170
01:03:17.293 --> 01:03:21.126
because we have
so many shared experiences.

1171
01:03:21.210 --> 01:03:24.001
a lot of them challenging.
a lot of them glorious.

1172
01:03:24.085 --> 01:03:27.460
We have a shortcut
for so many things we can say.

1173
01:03:27.543 --> 01:03:29.168
No one else
would ever understand us.

1174
01:03:29.251 --> 01:03:31.585
- Or "grasscutter for dinner."
