1509
01:20:11.210 --> 01:20:13.585
and. like.
missing my kids' play.

1510
01:20:13.669 --> 01:20:15.335
I'm like.
"What the--am I doing?"

1511
01:20:15.418 --> 01:20:16.293
You know?

1512
01:20:16.377 --> 01:20:17.502
And. like.
I probably won't get the job.

1513
01:20:17.585 --> 01:20:20.293
I didn't get the job.
And I'm like. "This is insane."

1514
01:20:20.377 --> 01:20:23.126
I want to just be present.

1515
01:20:28.877 --> 01:20:30.418
- This is one
of the best places

1516
01:20:30.502 --> 01:20:32.835
to bike and run and swim.

1517
01:20:32.919 --> 01:20:37.627
Because of that. there's
high demand to live here.

1518
01:20:37.710 --> 01:20:40.502
My wife was a professional
distance runner.

1519
01:20:40.585 --> 01:20:42.502
I was a professional
triathlete.

1520
01:20:42.585 --> 01:20:47.335
We started a company making
food products for ourselves.

1521
01:20:47.418 --> 01:20:51.293
Bend is a place where people
move because they want to.

1522
01:20:51.377 --> 01:20:54.043
It means that
you will even work in a job

1523
01:20:54.126 --> 01:20:55.710
that you're maybe less
fulfilled in

1524
01:20:55.794 --> 01:20:57.710
because you can
fulfill yourself

1525
01:20:57.794 --> 01:20:59.335
in the other aspects
of your life.

1526
01:20:59.418 --> 01:21:00.877
primarily in recreation.

1527
01:21:00.960 --> 01:21:02.460
There's
a general understanding

1528
01:21:02.543 --> 01:21:03.960
in the business community

1529
01:21:04.043 --> 01:21:05.960
that if it's a fresh-powder
day. your employees

1530
01:21:06.043 --> 01:21:07.960
probably aren't going to be in
until 11:00 or 12:00.

1531
01:21:08.043 --> 01:21:10.877
And we support that.

1532
01:21:10.960 --> 01:21:12.085
- Yeah!

1533
01:21:12.168 --> 01:21:13.877
- It's just a little bit
different priority system.

1534
01:21:13.960 --> 01:21:15.710
value system. I think.

1535
01:21:15.794 --> 01:21:16.710
- You got that!

1536
01:21:16.794 --> 01:21:18.335
- That's part of why
we live here.

1537
01:21:18.418 --> 01:21:19.710
- Yee-haw!

1538
01:21:21.377 --> 01:21:23.877
- Bend has over 20 brewpubs

1539
01:21:23.960 --> 01:21:26.168
and is the home
of Deschutes beer.

1540
01:21:26.251 --> 01:21:29.251
After first-hand research
all over the country.

1541
01:21:29.335 --> 01:21:32.377
we've determined that the
number of breweries in a town

1542
01:21:32.460 --> 01:21:35.502
is a great indicator
of how it's doing overall.

1543
01:21:41.627 --> 01:21:44.710
- I was voted most likely
to succeed in high school.

1544
01:21:44.794 --> 01:21:46.543
and that's still--
that still is gonna happen.

1545
01:21:47.835 --> 01:21:49.210
Here we go.

1546
01:21:49.293 --> 01:21:51.585
- Work it. work it.
- Work it. work it.

1547
01:21:51.669 --> 01:21:55.460
In Bend. freelance can be
really ups and downs.

1548
01:21:56.960 --> 01:22:02.543
My dad moved to Bend in 1962.

1549
01:22:02.627 --> 01:22:06.752
And he worked for
Brooks-Scanlon. the sawmill.

1550
01:22:06.835 --> 01:22:10.251
- And so the Bend of the 1960s
when you came here.

1551
01:22:10.335 --> 01:22:12.960
what was it like?
- It was just a mill town.

1552
01:22:14.460 --> 01:22:19.460
And the Brooks-Scanlon Lumber
Company was a huge operation.

1553
01:22:19.543 --> 01:22:20.877
- Like West Virginia.

1554
01:22:20.960 --> 01:22:24.710
Oregon's economy
always depended on one thing.

1555
01:22:24.794 --> 01:22:27.251
In West Virginia. it was coal.

1556
01:22:27.335 --> 01:22:31.126
In Oregon. it was trees.

1557
01:22:31.210 --> 01:22:34.418
But in the 1980s.
the timber industry crashed.

1558
01:22:34.502 --> 01:22:36.585
and sawmills closed.

1559
01:22:36.669 --> 01:22:40.418
Bend suddenly had the highest
unemployment in the country.

1560
01:22:40.502 --> 01:22:42.335
- It was pretty staggering.

1561
01:22:42.418 --> 01:22:44.251
We had a lot of mill workers

1562
01:22:44.335 --> 01:22:47.794
that had a lot of skills
and nowhere to go.

1563
01:22:47.877 --> 01:22:51.460
It was really hard
on most people.

1564
01:22:51.543 --> 01:22:54.168
- Downtown Bend
was kind of boarded up.

1565
01:22:54.251 --> 01:22:55.710
- There was a saying in Bend.
you know.

1566
01:22:55.794 --> 01:22:57.293
"The last one to leave
downtown.

1567
01:22:57.377 --> 01:22:59.001
turn out the lights."

1568
01:22:59.085 --> 01:23:02.251
- Bend was pretty empty
when I was a kid.

1569
01:23:02.335 --> 01:23:05.669
I think that Bend was really
kind of grasping

1570
01:23:05.752 --> 01:23:08.168
for what was gonna be next.

1571
01:23:08.251 --> 01:23:10.585
My friends. whose parents were
in other industries.

1572
01:23:10.669 --> 01:23:11.627
there was hope.

1573
01:23:11.710 --> 01:23:13.960
More tourism was starting
to happen.

1574
01:23:14.043 --> 01:23:15.669
Bend has always had
Mount Bachelor to rely on.

1575
01:23:15.752 --> 01:23:18.001
and people were
still coming to ski.

1576
01:23:18.085 --> 01:23:21.585
- We began to realize a lot
of people were moving here

1577
01:23:21.669 --> 01:23:23.126
who had come here on vacation.

1578
01:23:23.210 --> 01:23:25.126
They may have come to ski.

1579
01:23:25.210 --> 01:23:28.043
But then they said. "You know.
this is a pretty nice town."

1580
01:23:28.126 --> 01:23:31.168
- Mike Hollern was also
at Brooks-Scanlon.

1581
01:23:31.251 --> 01:23:34.001
He saw that the land where
they once grew timber

1582
01:23:34.085 --> 01:23:38.126
could be used
to build communities.

1583
01:23:38.210 --> 01:23:41.043
They created a series
of planned neighborhoods

1584
01:23:41.126 --> 01:23:43.085
designed to encourage
a social life.

1585
01:23:43.168 --> 01:23:45.543
with front porches
and back alleys.

1586
01:23:49.043 --> 01:23:51.543
Stores and schools are close
to houses.

1587
01:23:51.627 --> 01:23:53.710
- The reason that people like
living on the Westside of Bend

1588
01:23:53.794 --> 01:23:56.085
is that you can walk
everywhere you want to go.

1589
01:23:56.168 --> 01:23:57.168
That's not always available

1590
01:23:57.251 --> 01:23:59.377
in the newer. suburban model
of development.

1591
01:24:02.043 --> 01:24:03.835
- As the mills were
shutting down.

1592
01:24:03.919 --> 01:24:06.669
a plan to turn them
into a retail district

1593
01:24:06.752 --> 01:24:09.001
was led by Bill Smith.

1594
01:24:09.085 --> 01:24:12.543
- When the sawmill closed.
they had 30 people employed.

1595
01:24:14.126 --> 01:24:16.752
Now there's 4.000 people
employed in the area.

1596
01:24:26.502 --> 01:24:30.710
- Bend has become this haven
for remote workers

1597
01:24:30.794 --> 01:24:34.877
that work for companies
outside of Oregon.

1598
01:24:34.960 --> 01:24:36.210
I tell entrepreneurs.

1599
01:24:36.293 --> 01:24:39.251
"You can build your business
anywhere today."

1600
01:24:39.335 --> 01:24:41.669
Technology allows that.

1601
01:24:41.752 --> 01:24:43.293
Capital and your customers

1602
01:24:43.377 --> 01:24:45.085
don't care
where you're located.

1603
01:24:56.460 --> 01:24:59.251
- Deschutes County has
about 6.000 people a year

1604
01:24:59.335 --> 01:25:01.251
moving into the county.

1605
01:25:01.335 --> 01:25:03.585
So many new people
are moving in.

1606
01:25:03.669 --> 01:25:04.919
A lot of times. this is

1607
01:25:05.001 --> 01:25:06.085
the first place people will go

1608
01:25:06.168 --> 01:25:07.251
because they don't know

1609
01:25:07.335 --> 01:25:08.835
anybody else in the community

1610
01:25:08.919 --> 01:25:12.210
and they need to start making
some social connections.

1611
01:25:13.835 --> 01:25:17.251
Last night. we had a program
out at a brewery in here town

1612
01:25:17.335 --> 01:25:19.210
with author Rich Benjamin.

1613
01:25:20.460 --> 01:25:23.627
- I've written a book called
"Searching for Whitopia."

1614
01:25:23.710 --> 01:25:25.877
How do I define a whitopia?

1615
01:25:25.960 --> 01:25:28.960
That it is at least 85% white.

1616
01:25:29.043 --> 01:25:33.460
the majority of that growth
has been from white residents.

1617
01:25:33.543 --> 01:25:36.126
- Bend has more than 90%
white people.

1618
01:25:36.210 --> 01:25:37.919
Why is that happening?

1619
01:25:38.001 --> 01:25:40.085
- About white-on-white
gentrification.

1620
01:25:40.168 --> 01:25:42.293
- Last night was
a really great conversation

1621
01:25:42.377 --> 01:25:45.126
for how we can embrace
diversity.

1622
01:25:45.210 --> 01:25:47.126
How do we make this
a welcoming place

1623
01:25:47.210 --> 01:25:50.001
for people that are moving
into Deschutes County?

1624
01:25:53.168 --> 01:25:56.418
- If I could change anything
in Bend. it would be diversity.

1625
01:25:56.502 --> 01:25:59.251
- Tom Bedell and his stepson.
RA Beattie.

1626
01:25:59.335 --> 01:26:01.502
make custom guitars in Bend.

1627
01:26:09.710 --> 01:26:13.126
What would the naysayers say
is wrong with Bend?

1628
01:26:13.210 --> 01:26:14.835
- It's too big.

1629
01:26:14.919 --> 01:26:16.126
- Yeah. if they got here first.

1630
01:26:16.210 --> 01:26:18.293
they would now say
it's too big.

1631
01:26:18.377 --> 01:26:19.335
I wouldn't say that.

1632
01:26:19.418 --> 01:26:21.669
So there's always pressure.
you know?

1633
01:26:21.752 --> 01:26:24.168
Like. now that I live here.
Californians. stay home.

1634
01:26:24.251 --> 01:26:25.335
- Right?

1635
01:26:25.418 --> 01:26:27.627
- Yeah.
- But that's not fair.

1636
01:26:27.710 --> 01:26:28.835
- It's really hard to complain

1637
01:26:28.919 --> 01:26:31.669
about the people that
are making your economy work.

1638
01:26:31.752 --> 01:26:34.502
- Growth is fascinating
because communities think

1639
01:26:34.585 --> 01:26:37.877
that the secret
to their...

1640
01:26:37.960 --> 01:26:40.335
prosperity is growth.

1641
01:26:40.418 --> 01:26:41.460
And I believe

1642
01:26:41.543 --> 01:26:45.335
that our whole culture
is gonna go through a change

1643
01:26:45.418 --> 01:26:48.001
to where growth
isn't "the ideal thing."

1644
01:26:48.085 --> 01:26:51.335
If climate change comes
from growth. right?

1645
01:26:51.418 --> 01:26:54.001
Expanding economies
isn't necessarily

1646
01:26:54.085 --> 01:26:57.669
adding to the quality of life
of humans on this planet.

1647
01:26:57.752 --> 01:27:01.043
- The real question is.
how do you grow in a fashion

1648
01:27:01.126 --> 01:27:05.752
that doesn't create continued
reliance upon the automobile?

1649
01:27:05.835 --> 01:27:07.418
I have so many friends now

1650
01:27:07.502 --> 01:27:09.377
that are looking
to either move out of town

1651
01:27:09.460 --> 01:27:11.210
because they can no longer
afford to live here

1652
01:27:11.293 --> 01:27:13.418
or are forced to commute
30 minutes a day.

1653
01:27:13.502 --> 01:27:14.752
And so that sort of corrodes

1654
01:27:14.835 --> 01:27:16.377
a community.
you know. cohesiveness

1655
01:27:16.460 --> 01:27:17.877
because it
no longer allows people

1656
01:27:17.960 --> 01:27:19.418
to live in the communities
where they work.

1657
01:27:32.794 --> 01:27:36.502
- Who determines a town's
relationship to nature?

1658
01:27:38.669 --> 01:27:40.293
There are still places

1659
01:27:40.377 --> 01:27:43.293
where you can imagine
a world without people.

1660
01:27:46.293 --> 01:27:51.418
When Europeans arrived. they
carved out farms and ranches.

1661
01:27:51.502 --> 01:27:55.877
Small towns were places
to buy and sell goods.

1662
01:27:55.960 --> 01:27:58.293
But as the country
industrialized.

1663
01:27:58.377 --> 01:28:02.710
the landscape turned into
something unrecognizable...

1664
01:28:05.460 --> 01:28:08.543
Or these days.
all too recognizable

1665
01:28:08.627 --> 01:28:10.543
because the same strip malls.

1666
01:28:10.627 --> 01:28:14.543
box stores. and chain
restaurants are everywhere.

1667
01:28:26.710 --> 01:28:30.835
And when nature is erased.
how can you ever get it back?

1668
01:28:30.919 --> 01:28:33.418
It's a tense question in Bend.

1669
01:28:47.794 --> 01:28:50.293
- My name's Sky Sharp.
and what we do here

1670
01:28:50.377 --> 01:28:53.418
is we raise beef
in a good way.

1671
01:28:53.502 --> 01:28:56.335
and we sell it farm to table.

1672
01:28:59.543 --> 01:29:01.627
I chose this life
a long time ago

1673
01:29:01.710 --> 01:29:05.669
because it was just where
I felt right. you know?

1674
01:29:05.752 --> 01:29:08.126
My whole adult life.
I've been a cowboy.

1675
01:29:08.210 --> 01:29:12.001
Like. bunched cows
and rode horses.

1676
01:29:12.085 --> 01:29:16.502
I just ended up
really liking cows

1677
01:29:16.585 --> 01:29:18.710
more than I liked people.

1678
01:29:20.418 --> 01:29:24.377
My horses and my dogs.
we try to work as a unit.

1679
01:29:28.210 --> 01:29:29.835
In the five years
that we've been here.

1680
01:29:29.919 --> 01:29:31.085
it's growing so fast

1681
01:29:31.168 --> 01:29:35.669
as far as people moving
from California and wherever.

1682
01:29:35.752 --> 01:29:37.418
Lots of farms and ranches

1683
01:29:37.502 --> 01:29:41.293
getting turned
into subdivisions.

1684
01:29:41.377 --> 01:29:43.919
Doesn't feel like communities
see food producers

1685
01:29:44.001 --> 01:29:46.460
as necessity.

1686
01:29:47.794 --> 01:29:49.043
It's hard.

1687
01:29:49.126 --> 01:29:51.335
I met those cows
when they're born.

1688
01:29:51.418 --> 01:29:55.543
You know.
I witnessed their first steps.

1689
01:29:55.627 --> 01:29:59.543
And I also take away
their last breath. you know?

1690
01:29:59.627 --> 01:30:01.752
So it's emotionally tough.

1691
01:30:10.669 --> 01:30:13.752
I love watching the subtleties
of things

1692
01:30:13.835 --> 01:30:16.418
that always reminds me
as a human being

1693
01:30:16.502 --> 01:30:18.919
that I'm part
of something much bigger.

1694
01:30:21.293 --> 01:30:23.377
My whole life. I've felt
like I had a purpose.

1695
01:30:23.460 --> 01:30:25.585
and that purpose was
to be a shepherd

1696
01:30:25.669 --> 01:30:29.585
and a steward to nature.

1697
01:30:29.669 --> 01:30:31.960
That's what we try to do here.

1698
01:30:58.710 --> 01:31:00.251
- We started this project

1699
01:31:00.335 --> 01:31:03.710
in the wake
of a global financial crisis.

1700
01:31:03.794 --> 01:31:05.085
And as we finish.

1701
01:31:05.168 --> 01:31:07.585
the world is dealing
with upheavals

1702
01:31:07.669 --> 01:31:09.251
on a historic scale.

1703
01:31:12.210 --> 01:31:15.126
- The pandemic has transformed
just about everything.

1704
01:31:19.543 --> 01:31:22.126
And inequalities
in race and class

1705
01:31:22.210 --> 01:31:24.502
are now in everyone's sight.

1706
01:31:28.919 --> 01:31:30.293
- It's easy to forget

1707
01:31:30.377 --> 01:31:34.001
that our history is full
of convulsive moments.

1708
01:31:47.418 --> 01:31:51.085
Every town has had
its heartbreaks and setbacks.

1709
01:31:52.919 --> 01:31:56.502
And these days. every town
is dealing with new ones.

1710
01:31:59.877 --> 01:32:01.710
- On this journey. we've seen

1711
01:32:01.794 --> 01:32:05.001
how towns have pulled
themselves up in the past.

1712
01:32:05.085 --> 01:32:07.710
We can learn
from how they did it.

1713
01:32:09.835 --> 01:32:12.085
Recovery takes
working together.

1714
01:32:12.168 --> 01:32:14.960
It's harder
in polarized times.

1715
01:32:15.043 --> 01:32:17.919
but towns do it
by focusing on local issues

1716
01:32:18.001 --> 01:32:21.043
that are outside the divisions
of national politics.

1717
01:32:23.585 --> 01:32:25.001
- Each town has individuals

1718
01:32:25.085 --> 01:32:28.543
who feel a responsibility
to their community.

1719
01:32:28.627 --> 01:32:32.251
- We tried a lot
of different things with you.

1720
01:32:32.335 --> 01:32:33.752
Nobody gave up on you.

1721
01:32:33.835 --> 01:32:37.210
so we don't want you giving up
on yourself.

1722
01:32:37.293 --> 01:32:40.835
- Democracy has always
depended on leadership.

1723
01:32:40.919 --> 01:32:44.502
- The woman chief is powerful.
The women ruled.

1724
01:32:44.585 --> 01:32:47.210
I don't know
how it shifted to the men.

1725
01:32:47.293 --> 01:32:49.585
I hope these girls look at me
and say.

1726
01:32:49.669 --> 01:32:52.752
"I could be that
